The '''white-eyed buzzard''' ('''''Butastur teesa''''') is a medium-sized [[hawk]], distinct from the true buzzards in the genus ''[[Buteo]]'', found in [[South Asia]]. Adults have a rufous tail, a distinctive white iris, and a white throat bearing a dark mesial stripe bordered. The head is brown and the median coverts of the upper wing are pale. They lack the typical carpal patches on the underside of the wings seen in true buzzards, but the entire wing lining appears dark in contrast to the flight feathers. They sit upright on perches for prolonged periods and soar on thermals in search of insect and small vertebrate prey. They are vociferous in the breeding season, and several birds may be heard calling as they soar together.

==Description==
[[File:White-eyed buzzard hawk (India, 2012).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Adult, note the pale appearance to the median upperwing coverts]]

This slim and small hawk is easily identified by its white iris  and the white throat and dark mesial stripe. A white spot is sometimes visible on the back of the head. When perched, the wing tip nearly reaches the tip of the tail. The ceres are distinctly yellow and the head is dark with the underside of the body darkly barred. In flight, the narrow wings appear rounded with black tips to the feathers and the wing lining appears dark. The upper wing in flight shows a pale bar over the brown. The rufous tail is barred with a darker subterminal band. Young birds have the iris brownish and the forehead is whitish and a broad supercilium may be present.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/myscrapbookorrou00hume#page/286/mode/2up/search/teesa| pages=286–288|author=Hume, AO|author-link=Allan Octavian Hume|year=1869|title=My Scrap Book: Rough notes on Indian oology and ornithology|publisher=Baptist Mission Press, Calcutta }}</ref> The only confusion can occur in places where it overlaps with the [[grey-faced buzzard]] (''Butastur indicus''), adults of which have a distinctive white supercilium.<ref name=pcr>{{cite book|author1=Rasmussen PC  |author2=JC Anderton |name-list-style=amp | year=2005| title= Birds of South Asia. The Ripley Guide. Volume 2|pages=100–101|publisher=Smithsonian Institution & Lynx Edicions}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Clark, William S |author2=Schmitt, N John |year=1992 |title= Flight identification of indian raptors with pale bars on upper wings| journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=89|issue=1|pages=1–3|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48732507}}</ref> Fledgelings are reddish brown, unlike most other downy raptor chicks, which tend to be white.<ref>{{cite journal|author= Gnanaselvan, P |year=1992| title= Nesting of the White-eyed Buzzard-Eagle in Pudukudi, Thanjavur District|journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] | volume=32|issue=7&8| pages=16–17|url=https://archive.org/stream/NLBW32_78#page/n17/mode/1up}}</ref>

== Taxonomy and systematics ==
The specific name ''teesa'' is derived from the name in Hindi.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jerdon, TC|year=1862 |title=The Birds of India. volume 1|url=https://archive.org/stream/birdsofindiabein01jerd#page/92/mode/2up/search/teesa|pages=92–93|publisher=Military Orphan Press, Calcutta}}</ref> The species was described on the basis of specimens collected by James Franklin who placed it in the genus ''Circus'' along with the harriers.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Franklin, James|year=1831|title=Catalogue of Birds which were collected on the Ganges between Calcutta nad Benares, and in the Vindhyian hills between the latter place and Gurrah Mundela, on the Nerbudda|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/12861523|journal=Proceedings of the Committee of Science and Correspondence of the Zoological Society of London|pages=114–125}}</ref> The name ''Butastur'' was used to indicate that it appeared to be intermediate in characters to the ''Buteo'' buzzards and ''Astur'', an old name for the sparrowhawks. Molecular phylogeny studies suggest that the genus is a sister group of ''Buteo'' and its relatives within the subfamily Buteoninae.<ref>{{cite journal|title= Molecular Phylogenetics of the Buteonine Birds of Prey (Accipitridae)|author=Lerner, HRL|author2=Matthew C. Klaver, David P. Mindell |name-list-style=amp |journal= The Auk |year=2008|volume=125|issue=2|pages=304–315|doi= 10.1525/auk.2008.06161|s2cid=85907449|doi-access=free}}</ref>

==Distribution and habitat==
[[File:WEBuzzard DSC0668 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|A young bird]]

This species is widely distributed in South Asia, throughout India in the plains and extending up to 1000 m in the [[Himalaya]]s. It is a resident in Iran, Pakistan, Nepal, Bangladesh, and Myanmar. A form that is possibly of this species has been recorded in the Greater Sundas, [[Indonesia]] but this population is widely disjunct and has whiter and unmarked feathers on the thigh or "trousers" and vent, possibly representing a new form.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Shagir|first1=K. J.|last2=Iqbal|first2=M.|title=White-eyed Buzzard Butastur teesa, a new species for Greater Sundas and Wallacea|journal=BirdingAsia|date=2015|issue=23|pages=124–125|access-date=5 August 2015|url=https://www.academia.edu/14211818}}</ref> It is absent from Sri Lanka and is probably absent from the Andamans. It is a summer visitor in northeastern Afghanistan. It is mainly found in the plains, but may go up to 1200 m altitude in the foothills of the Himalayas.<ref name="pcr" />

The usual habitat is in dry, open forest or cultivation. They are numerous in some areas, but declining.<ref name="pcr" /> A survey in the late 1950s estimated about 5000 birds in the vicinity of Delhi in an area of about 50,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> giving a density of 0.1 per square kilometre.<ref>{{cite journal|title=A comparative analysis of the density of predatory birds in two selected areas within the Palaearctic and Oriental regions, near Moscow and Delhi|author=Galushin VM|year=1975|journal=Emu|volume=74|pages=330–335|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/?act=view_file&file_id=MU974330.pdf|doi=10.1071/MU974330 }}</ref>

==Behaviour and ecology==
This species is usually seen soaring alone in thermals or perched still. Groups of two or three may sometimes be seen. They have a mewing call or falling whistle (transcribed as ''pit-weer''<ref>{{cite book|author=Whistler, Hugh|year=1949| title= Popular handbook of Indian Birds| publisher=Gurney and Jackson|pages=366–367| url=https://archive.org/stream/popularhandbooko033226mbp#page/n417/mode/2up/search/butastur}}</ref>) that is repeated when pairs are soaring.<ref name="pcr" /> They are vociferous in the breeding season.<ref>{{cite book|pages=32–36|url=https://archive.org/stream/junglefolkindian00dewa#page/32/mode/2up/search/butastur|title=Jungle Folk: Indian natural history|publisher=John Lane|year=1912|author=Dewar, Douglas}}</ref>

