They feed mainly on locusts, grasshoppers, crickets, and other large insects, as well as mice, lizards, and frogs. They may also take crabs from near wetlands<ref>{{cite journal|author=Mackenzie, K |year=1894| title= Food of the white-eyed buzzard| journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=9|issue=1|page=101|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30887606}}</ref> and have been reported to take larger prey such as the [[black-naped hare]] (''Lepus nigricollis'').<ref>{{cite journal|author=Javed, Salim |year=1995| title= Hare in the diet of White-eyed Buzzard Eagle ''Butastur teesa'' (Franklin)|journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=92|issue=1|page=119|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48613652}}</ref>

The breeding season is February to May. The nest is loose platform of twigs not unlike that of a crow, sometimes placed in a leafless tree.<ref>{{cite journal| title=Nesting site of white-eyed buzzard in Kanha National Park|author=Kanoje, R|journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] | page=90|url=https://archive.org/stream/NLBW37_5#page/n20/mode/1up|volume=37|issue=5|year=1997}}</ref> The usual clutch is three eggs, which are white and usually unspotted.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://archive.org/stream/faunaofbritishin03oate#page/362/mode/1up/|pages=362–364|title= The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma. Birds. Volume 3| year=1895|publisher= Taylor and Francis|place=London|author=Blanford, W.T.}}</ref> Both sexes share nest-building and feeding young; the female alone incubates for about 19 days until the eggs hatch.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Soni, R.G. |year=1993 |title= Breeding of White-eyed Buzzard in the Thar Desert| journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.  |volume=90|issue=3|pages=506–507|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48609777}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|pages=158–161|url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924000044994#page/n179/mode/2up/search/butastur|title=The nests and eggs of Indian birds. Volume 3|publisher=R H Porter, London|author=Hume, AO|year=1890}}</ref><ref name=hbk>{{cite book|author1=Ali S  |author2=SD Ripley |name-list-style=amp |pages=256–258|title=Handbook of the Birds of India and Pakistan. Volume 1|edition=2nd| year=1978|publisher=Oxford University Press|place=New Delhi}}</ref>

A species of endoparasitic [[platyhelminth]] has been described from the liver of this species.<ref>{{cite journal|title=''Uvitellina teesae'', new species (Digenea: Cyclocoelidae) from liver of white-eyed buzzard ''Butastur teesa'' (Accipitridae), in Hala, Hyderabad, Sindh, Pakistan|author=Dharejo, A.M. Bilqees|author2=F.M. Khan, M.M.| journal=Pakistan Journal of Zoology|year=2007 |volume=39| issue=6|pages=385–388}}</ref> A species of nematode, ''Contracaecum milvi'', has been recorded in the liver and the stomach<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Inglis|first=William G.|date=1954|title=On some nematodes from Indian vertebrates. I. Birds|journal=Annals and Magazine of Natural History|language=en|volume=7|issue=83|pages=821–826|doi=10.1080/00222935408651795|issn=0374-5481}}</ref> while [[Acanthocephala]]ns, ''Mediorhynchus gibson and M. fatimae'', has been described from the gut of specimens from Pakistan.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Bilqees, F. M.|author2=Khan, A.|author3=Khatoon, N.|author4=Khatoon, Sh.|year=2007|title=Acanthocephala from eagle of Karachi with descriptions of two new species.|journal=Proceedings of Parasitology|volume=43|pages=15–26}}</ref> Protozoa that live in the blood stream belonging to the genus ''Atoxoplasma'' have been isolated.<ref>{{cite journal| title=The Genus Atoxoplasma (Protozoa, Apicomplexa)| author=Levine, Norman D| journal=Journal of Parasitology |volume=68|issue=4|year=1982|pages=719–723| doi=10.2307/3280933| pmid=7119994| jstor=3280933| doi-access=free}}</ref> Like most birds, they have specialized ectoparasitic [[Bird louse|bird lice]] such as ''Colpocephalum zerafae'' that are also known from other birds of prey.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Etudes sur les Colpocephalum (Mallophaga, Menoponidae) parasites des Falconiforms 1. Groupe ''zerafae'' Price & Beer|journal=Bonn. Zool. Beitr.|volume=39|pages=77–102|year=1988|author=Tendeiro, J|url=http://www.phthiraptera.org/Publications/4858.pdf|archive-date=2014-12-19|access-date=2009-11-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219075100/http://www.phthiraptera.org/Publications/4858.pdf}}</ref> A study of power lines in Rajasthan in 2011 found white-eyed buzzards to be the second most common raptor killed by electrocution after kestrels.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Harness, R.H.|author2=Juvvadi, P.R.|author3=Dwyer, J.F.|title=Avian electrocutions in western Rajasthan, India|journal=J. Raptor Res.|year=2013|volume=47|issue=4|pages=352–364|doi=10.3356/JRR-13-00002.1|s2cid=36239163|doi-access=free}}</ref>

